ironic self-consciousness. In addition to thus identifying Beethoven's music as an overarching expression of values central to the age of Goethe and Hegel, the author describes and then critiques the process by which the musical values of the heroic style quickly became the controlling model of compositional logic in Western music criticism and analysis. Apart from its importance for students of Beethoven, this book will appeal to those interested in canon formation in the arts and in music as a cultural, ethical, and emotional force--and to anyone concerned with what we want from music and what music does for us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMusic audiences. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aAbbate, Carolyn.  aAdorno, Theodor.  aBeethoven Hero.  aBildungsroman.  aCone, Edward T.  aDahlhaus, Carl.  aEroica Symphony.  aFifth Symphony.  aForchert, Arno.  aGreene, David B.  aHalm, August.  aHomer.  aHyer, Brian.  aIliad.  aKnittel, Kristin M.  aKretzschmar, Hermann.  aLenz, Wilhelm von.  aLorenz, Alfred.  aMann, Thomas.  aMcClary, Susan.  aOster, Ernst.  aRatner, Leonard.  aRiemann, Hugo.  aRosen, Charles.  aSchering, Arnold.  aSchleuning, Peter.  aTovey, Donald Francis.  acanon, in music.  adiegesis.  aergon.  airony.  anarration, in music.  aprotagonist, dramatic.  asonata form.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691215884zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691215884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691215884.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACK